OSG assigns full control grant to the object owner in addition to any canned ACLs specified in the headers at the time of object creation. This logic aligned with S3 behavior in the us-east region around the time OSG was introduced (2013). Examine the logic that expands canned ACLs into grants in [AclUtils.java|https://github.com/eucalyptus/eucalyptus/blob/4f77de7dd5b2f59164f46f1bd2a0f466a815b9a7/clc/modules/object-storage-common/src/main/java/com/eucalyptus/objectstorage/util/AclUtils.java#L223]. Every canned ACL builder invokes a PrivateOnlyGrantBuilder that is responsible for adding full control grant to the object owner. I would also follow up on all other (non-canned ACL builder) invocations of this logic.
{noformat}
protected enum AuthenticatedReadGrantBuilder implements Function<OwnerIdPair, List<Grant>> {
    INSTANCE;

    @Override
    public List<Grant> apply(OwnerIdPair ownerIds) {
      List<Grant> authenticatedRead = PrivateOnlyGrantBuilder.INSTANCE.apply(ownerIds);
      Grantee authenticatedUsers = new Grantee();
      authenticatedUsers.setGroup(new Group(ObjectStorageProperties.S3_GROUP.AUTHENTICATED_USERS_GROUP.toString()));
      Grant authUsersGrant = new Grant();
      authUsersGrant.setPermission(ObjectStorageProperties.Permission.READ.toString());
      authUsersGrant.setGrantee(authenticatedUsers);
      authenticatedRead.add(authUsersGrant);
      return authenticatedRead;
    }
  }

  ;
{noformat} 
Please be aware that canned ACLs apply to both buckets and objects, and changes to this logic would very likely impact both the resources.

